<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>MEMORANDUM FROM THE NATURAL ENVIRONMENT RESEARCH COUNCIL AND ITS RESEARCH CENTRES IN RESPONSE TO THE ENERGY AND CLIMATE CHANGE COMMITTEE INQUIRY INTO THE IPCC 5TH ASSESSMENT REVIEW</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Natural Environment Research Council (IPC0036)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Natural Environment Research Council (NERC) is one of the UK’s seven Research Councils. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It funds and carries out impartial scientific research in the sciences of the environment and trains the next generation of independent environmental scientists. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Details of NERC’s research centres and research programmes are available at </span><a href="http://www.nerc.ac.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.nerc.ac.uk</span></a><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This response is based on input from the British Antarctic Survey (BAS), the Centre for Ecology and Hydrology (CEH), the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">National Centre for Atmospheric Science (NCAS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the National Centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for Earth Observation (NCEO) and the National Oceanography Centre (NOC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, each of which is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">research centre operated by NERC.  Taken together, these centres employ around 730 research scie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntists, many of whom are engaged in climate-related research, including several Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Working Group 1 (IPCC WG1) Lead and Contributing Authors.  The responses to the Committee’s questions below are based on the views and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> experience of leading climate scientists from these Centres.  We have restricted ourselves to answering those questions that focus on the science presented in the IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Assessment Report (AR5).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 1:  How robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How much scope is there to question of the report’s conclusions? </span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are convinced that the headline conclusions of the report (those presented in brown boxes in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Summary for Policymakers) are robust. All findings are presented with appropriate assessed confidence levels.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 2:  Have the IPCC adequately addressed criticisms of previous reports?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2010, following criticism of the 4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> IPCC Assessment Report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (AR4), the UN and the IPCC chair commissioned a review of the IPCC’s processes and procedures by the Inter-Academy Council.  This report (</span><a href="http://reviewipcc.interacademycouncil.net"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://reviewipcc.interacademycouncil.net</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ) found that “the I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCC assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ss has been successful overall” but also made recommendations on changes to the IPCC’s governance, review process and the way in which uncertainty was communicated.  The IPCC implemented many of the recommendations of the Inter-Academy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Council review before AR5 was produced.  We believe that, in its response to this review, the IPCC has adequately responded to criticisms of AR4 and earlier reports.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 3:  To what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate scientists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scientists at BAS, CEH, NCAS, NCEO and NOC collaborate with a wide sector of the climate science community, both in the UK and internationally.  From this perspective, we are able to say that the WG1 contribution to the AR5 does reflect the views of the ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">instream climate science community.  A large number of papers written by BAS, CEH, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NCAS, NCEO and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NOC scientists are cited in the report.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 4:  Can any of the areas of the science now be considered settled as a result of AR5’s publication, if so wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ich?  What areas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The report states unequivocally that the climate system has warmed, that human activity has been a significant contributor to this warming, and that continued emissions of greenhou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se gases will cause further warming and changes in all components of the climate system.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Global mean tempe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ratures and sea level rose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over the last century by an amount exceeding the amplitude of shorter-term variability.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, there is still substanti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al uncertainty about the impacts of this warming at a regional scale (e.g. how will the frequency of extreme weather events in the UK change?), decadal variability, and the response of other elements of the climate system (e.g. the hydrological and biogeoc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hemical cycles, global ocean circulation, polar ice sheets and sea ice) to warming.  Research now needs to focus on these areas of remaining uncertainty.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 5:  How effective is AR5 and the summary for policymakers in conveying what is meant by unce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rtainty in scientific terms?  Would a focus on risk rather than uncertainty be useful?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In producing AR5, the IPCC has been careful to use consistent and well-defined language to communicate uncertainty (see </span><a href="http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/supporting-material/uncertainty-guidance-note.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/supporting-material/uncertainty-guidance-note.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).  However, users of the report may not all fully understand the concept of scientific uncertainty.  Scientists, science communicators and end </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">users (e.g. business and policy makers) need to work together to develop a shared taxonomy of uncertainty that will enable the results of AR5 to inform business, economic and policy decisions.  WG1 generally uses likelihood language in preference to risk l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">anguage because risk assessments typically involve consideration not only of likelihood but also of impacts, and may therefore involve value judgements beyond the scope of physical science.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 6:  Does the AR5 address the reliability of climate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">models?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:13.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Yes, this is directly addressed in Chapter 9 of AR5. This chapter notes that models now robustly represent many aspects of the climate system (e.g. multi-decade trends in continental-scale surface temperature) but that effort is still required to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> improve model performance (e.g. representation of clouds and precipitation).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 7:  Has AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:6.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This topic is specifically addressed in Cha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pter 9 of AR5, which concludes that there is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">medium confidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (as defined in the document cited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">paragraph 8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) that the hiatus is substantially a result of natural internal variability of the climate system, which includes a possible redistribution of he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at within the ocean, combined with a reduced trend in external </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">radiative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> forcing.  This assessment implies that differences between observed and modelled temperature trends over 1998-2012 do not imply a lack of robustness in model projections.  Research pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pers published since AR5 was released add further support to this viewpoint.  Further understanding of the hiatus is a subject of ongoing research, e.g. to better quantify the role of heat absorbed into the deep ocean.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 8:  Do the AR5 Physical Sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ience Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:6.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The major conclusions of the WG1 contribution to AR5 are in line with, and often stronger than, the conclusions of previous IPCC Assessment Reports.  The WG1 report presents a synthesis of current understanding of the physical drivers of climate change.  O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n its own, this does not tell us anything about the economic costs of climate change or mitigating measures but it is an essential starting point for calculating these costs.  While IPCC Working Groups 2 (Impacts) and 3 (Mitigation) will address economic q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uestions to some degree in their contributions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(to be published in 2014), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to the AR5 there is a requirement for a continuing dialogue between climate scientists, economists and the business sector outside the IPCC process.  Indeed, there is a need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strengthen this dialogue.  The new NERC strategy (</span><a href="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/about/strategy/business.asp"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nerc.ac.uk/about/strategy/business.asp</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) places considerable emphasis on the importance of environmental scientists working with o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ther groups to meet societal needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and NERC is very much upping its game in this regard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 9:  Is the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scientific knowledge?  Or has it focussed on providing a justification for political commitmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">t?</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:6.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe that the IPCC process is an effective mechanism for synthesising scientific understanding of climate change, and the reports have closely followed the IPCC’s mandate to be “policy relevant”, not “policy prescriptive”.  The scope of the scie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nce covered by IPCC Working Group 1 has grown considerably over the lifetime of the IPCC and the production of these reports places a considerable burden on the climate science community.  This issue, and the requirement to ensure the assessments are as us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eful as possible to policy makers, need to be addressed through continued reviewing and improvement of the process.  The long gaps between reports and consensus approach does lead to delays in being able to incorporate the very latest scientific understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing into the assessments. We are not aware of any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence that the findings of the IPCC have been influenced by a need to justify political commitment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>